title.narrative: 1.2: QUALITY SOCIAL SERVICE PACKAGES (0-59 MONTHS)

description.narrative: 1.2: Improved, quality social service packages (for maternal and newborn health, child health, nutrition, water and sanitation, birth registration, early stimulation and development, pre-primary education, and social protection) are developed, enhanced and made available to girls and boys (0â€“59 months) and pregnant women especially, which contributes to Access To Quality Learning Opportunities, Early Detection And Treatment Of Malnutrition, Fast-Track The End Of Hiv/Aids, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Nutrition In Early Childhood, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women, Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Harnessing Power Of Business And Markets, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, increased proportions of girls and boys (0â€“59 months) and pregnant women, especially in targeted municipalities in six deprived provinces and peri-urban Luanda, have equitable access to and use essential quality social services (for maternal and newborn health, child health, nutrition, water and sanitation, birth registration, early stimulation and development, pre-primary education and social protection)

description.narrative: Within the COVID-19 pandemic context, UNICEF supported government and stakeholders strengthen COVID-19 control action with restored continuity of essential healthcare services, benefiting 77,323 pregnant women in antenatal care, with 27,741 deliveries in maternities in supported districts,;753,763;children aged 0-11 months vaccinated with third dose of Pentavalent vaccine,457,285pregnant women vaccinated against tetanus, and11 million doses of COVID-19 vaccines administered nationwide. With further support, enhanced WASH services were developed in schools in the southern provinces of Angola. Over 2.5 million Angolan children had their births registered, conferring them rights to social services and protection from violence and exploitation. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:06/01/2022
